We have to implement an stack data structure with queue. We can do this with a single queue or two queues.


Code(single queue):
class MyStack {

    private Queue<Integer> q;

    public MyStack() {
        
        q = new LinkedList<>();
    }
    
    public void push(int x) {
        q.add(x);

        for(int i = 0; i <q.size() -1; i++) q.add(q.poll());
        
    }
    
    public int pop() {
        return q.poll();
    }
    
    public int top() {
        return q.peek();
    }
    
    public boolean empty() {
        return q.isEmpty();
    }
}


code(two queues):
import java.util.*;

class MyStack {

    // q1 is the main queue.
    // We always keep the current stack top at the front of q1.
    Queue<Integer> q1;

    // q2 is a helper queue used during push.
    Queue<Integer> q2;

    public MyStack() {
        q1 = new LinkedList<>();
        q2 = new LinkedList<>();
    }
    
    public void push(int x) {
        // Step 1: Put the new element into q2 first.
        // Since stack is LIFO, this new element must become the top.
        q2.offer(x);

        // Step 2: Move all old elements from q1 to q2.
        // This places the new element before all older elements.
        while (!q1.isEmpty()) {
            q2.offer(q1.poll());
        }

        // Step 3: Swap q1 and q2.
        // Now q1 has the correct stack order.
        Queue<Integer> temp = q1;
        q1 = q2;
        q2 = temp;
    }
    
    public int pop() {
        // The stack top is always at the front of q1.
        // poll() removes and returns it.
        return q1.poll();
    }
    
    public int top() {
        // peek() returns the front element without removing it.
        return q1.peek();
    }
    
    public boolean empty() {
        // If q1 is empty, the stack is empty.
        return q1.isEmpty();
    }
}
